# .gitattributes — enforce line-ending policy per file type.
#
# Without this, Git's core.autocrlf setting can quietly rewrite line
# endings on checkout/commit, which has bitten this project twice:
#   1. backend/entrypoint.sh was committed with CRLF line terminators.
#      The Dockerfile.dev's `COPY . .` baked those CRLFs into the
#      image, then the entrypoint invoked `sh ./entrypoint.sh` and
#      dash barfed on `set -e\r` ("Illegal option -") — backend
#      container ended up in a restart loop on every `./dev start`.
#   2. Same pathology applies to any *.sh file edited in an editor
#      that writes CRLF on Windows. We want shell scripts to always
#      be LF, regardless of host OS or editor.
#
# Rule: all shell scripts MUST be LF in the repo. .gitattributes
# re-normalizes them on next checkout (text eol=lf), but existing
# files need a one-time `git add --renormalize` to flip them.

*.sh        text eol=lf
*.bash      text eol=lf
*.env       text eol=lf eol=lf

# Python source: LF by convention. No `eol=lf` here because we want
# it to stay portable (the existing files are already LF in repo).
*.py        text eol=lf

# JS / TS / JSON / YAML / TOML: LF (Windows editors sometimes
# introduce CRLF; this prevents it).
*.js        text eol=lf
*.ts        text eol=lf
*.tsx       text eol=lf
*.jsx       text eol=lf
*.json      text eol=lf
*.yaml      text eol=lf
*.yml       text eol=lf
*.toml      text eol=lf

# Dockerfile / compose: LF (docker tooling doesn't tolerate CRLF in
# RUN / COPY paths reliably).
Dockerfile*       text eol=lf
*.dockerfile      text eol=lf
docker-compose*.yml text eol=lf
docker-compose*.yaml text eol=lf

# Markdown: LF (lets GitHub render correctly). LF on render-side
# is fine; CRLF in .md just makes the diff noisy.
*.md         text eol=lf

# Plain text / log / gitignore / gitattributes: LF.
*.txt        text eol=lf
*.gitignore  text eol=lf
.gitattributes    text eol=lf

# Don't touch binary files explicitly — Git's default heuristic
# handles them correctly, and an explicit `-binary` rule here would
# prevent future binary additions from being tracked properly.